 <br>
In between, a mixture of innocents and some right evil cows, who poisoned their husband(s) or beat their servants to death, all step up to the gallows, stake, guillotine, cauldron! Some of the arsenic poisoners were the serial killers of their day and often managed to get away with multiple murders over a period of several years. It makes you wonder how many of these crimes went undetected.<br>
<br>
I've also been reading 'An Egyptian Panorama: Reports from the 19th century British Press,' which reproduces articles that appeared in British newspapers from the 1840s up to the 1900s. Of particular interest is a series of news stories detailing the perilous journey of Cleopatra's Needle, from Alexandria to its current home on the Thames Embankment in London. <br>
<br>
Although I have some a cursory interest in Egypt and the archaeological discoveries that were being made at the time, I bought this book for the artwork. These articles predate the use of photography in newspapers. The pictures that accompany the text were drawn by hand in incredible detail. They were then sent back to England where they were engraved onto box-tree printing stamps. This engraving process was often undertaken by candlelight, which makes the quality of the artwork all the more remarkable.<br>
<br>
The writing is typically colonial and very much of it's time, complete with some unpleasant racial epithets. In one of the opening stories an Englishman gives an account of how he spent the afternoon on the veranda of the Suez hotel pelting the natives with oranges. I've come across a few typos that obviously came about when the articles were copied out for publication in the book.<br>
<br>
I also have a hardback anthology of Douglas Dunn's poetry on the go and I'm about two thirds of the way through an immunology textbook, whose title escapes me<br>
<br>
